## Goals {#goals}

Maps in our game are both the canvas and the paint. Each map provides context clues for gameplay and objectives, a sense of direction for team play, and an aesthetic that complements the tone of the game. Each map should feel unique to play on and provide a different set of challenges.

## Definitions {#definitions}

A map is **unbounded** if the player cannot reach a finite wall. A good indication of a **bounded** map is provided by the in-game map (i.e. tap M). The next best indication is through walls displayed on a minimap. For our game, we place the players into a bounded map that is large relative to the player‚Äôs movement speed. Such that, in a given round, a player can only traverse the majority of the map with a significant movement speed buff.

The **environment** is defined by a combination of **biome** (the flora, fauna, and terrain) and **locale** (artifices or structures). Biomes are unique to a given planet and locales are unique to a given biome. For example:

1. **Environment:** Venoxarid Spawning Pools  
   1. Biome

      2. Green/yellow/pink color palette  
      3. Low plants that spit puffs of toxin  
      4. Minimal elevation changes, some caverns  
   2. Locale  
      1. Bubbly green pools of liquid  
      2. Incubation chamber  
      3. Egg sacs

**Objectives** are touch points throughout the map that are defined when the round starts. These should provide resources to the player that contribute to round-over-round survival. In contrast, **events** are a side effect of the environment or certain objectives and require a trigger. Triggers include proximity, killing enough of certain enemies, carrying a special item, etc. For example:

1. A player completes the ‚Äúdismantle ancient reactor‚Äù objective to acquire a part for the ship.  
2. On their way back to the ship, the player destroys all of the egg sacs in the Venoxarid spawning pools.  
3. This triggers the Venoxarid Queen event to appear on the map. She is an area boss with unique loot.

**The ship** is a key part of the map. It‚Äôs where players start, when they return to complete repairs and end the round, and it‚Äôs also where players manage meta progression without the pressure of encroaching enemies. The ship has a consistent size and appearance across all maps.

**Elevation** refers to a change in z-height on the same terrain (i.e. walking up a slope). **Verticality** refers to a change in z-height over dissimilar terrain (i.e. taking an elevator up or falling down a cliff). Changes in elevation *should not* cause projectile or melee attacks to miss. That is, the player‚Äôs character should be trusted to shoot/punch slightly up or down to account for a slope. A difference in verticality *should* cause melee attacks to miss but not most projectile attacks. That is, you cannot punch down a cliff but you can shoot down it.

**The storm** is a concept borrowed from the battle royale genre, where the available map area decreases during a round. This encourages players to be very adventurous at the start of a round or lose the chance to hit objectives.

## Key aspects of a map

For at least three reasons, maps need to be *very large* relative to the size of the player.

1. We do not want players to often retread ‚Äúdead space‚Äù in the map. The map should have new areas to explore every round.  
2. Advanced traversal skills should provide a competitive advantage. We should design maps that allow players to leverage advanced traversal in a fun and exciting way.  
3. We want players to feel like they‚Äôve landed in a big, unknown space. It should feel expansive, foreign, and dangerous.

Additionally, objectives on the map should be at least partly interchangeable. That is, objectives should be playable from multiple locations on any given instance of a map.
